Enjoyer Plan, Initial Attack: Scenario Alpha: Intel suggests that Pacifica will be stationing 197 troops in OK, and 180 troops in TX. In the event that does not change, here is Scenario Alpha: In this scenario, we will want to misinform Pacifica that Superior is planning an invasion of Arkansas to backdoor us. If Pacifica buys the story, we should not anticipate any further reinforcements to this front. We will instead stage a joint surprise invasion of OK from AR and MO. Stats are being kept on track the number of turns this operation will require (commitment), our chances of winning the battle (success), wiping out the enemy force outright (critical success), the most likely range of casualties we can expect to inflict (Casualties), the percentage of Pacifica’s army we stand to wipe out in the initial attack if we achieve critical success (Max Damage), and taking 100 or greater in losses (non-trivial failure). These percentages for Scenario Alpha are as follows:
  • Commitment: 1
  • Success: 77%
  • Critical Success: 53%
  • Casualties: 103-197
  • Max Damage: 28% (499 remaining)
  • Non-trivial failure: 12%
2:17 PM
Scenario Bravo: Under this scenario, we are attempting to draw more of Pacifica’s troops into the initial ambush to quickly and drastically decrease their ability to fight a prolonged war. The overall increased troop presence at the front in this scenario will require the misinformation sent to Pacifica to be far more load-bearing than under Scenario Alpha. Additional Superior troops will need to be pulled from ND, SD, KS, and NE. Superior will therefore need to lure Pacifica into a full false alliance, and perhaps commit to a false joint invasion against us, to ensure the integrity of the northern border. After our initial troop movement this turn, Pacifica will see the troop disparity at the border and move to relocate troops, creating a stalemate zone for their drafting strategy. If Pacifica is led to believe in an alliance with Superior, they will move troops down from MT and WY, as well as splitting their troops from CO, to accomplish this. We will then proceed the next turn with the joint invasion of OK from AR and MO.
  • Commitment: 2
  • Success: 70%
  • Critical Success: 41%
  • Casualties: 133-351
  • Max Damage: 50% (345 remaining)
  • Non-trivial failure: 21%

Großer Peanut 4/10/2024 10:25 PM
my personal thoughts
brakamonoga 4/10/2024 10:33 PM
Ultimately the problem isn’t alliances, it’s only having five factions. You can’t tell people they aren’t allowed to strategize, but when you have so few factions (and an odd number, no less), the game quickly becomes “two wolves and a sheep voting on what’s for dinner.” That’s why I’ve used the analogy of Survivor when explaining stuff to my faction. This game isn’t about numbers, it’s about building rapport and not getting voted off the island
10:33 PM
I think more factions would help make this much less of a problem
Großer Peanut 4/10/2024 10:38 PM
Thats a good point. Part of the problem is also having aligned goals. Allies of convenience are fine. If two factions decide they agree on everything and will never fight each other, thats just silly. We need a system that makes sure we are always assuming allies will betray each other when they can. Unfortunately, thats more about the mindset than the rules, tho theres some things you can do probably. Having more factions would help but I also think it would end up in two giant factions eventually. People would start to ally, others would realize they need allies to survive, and it snowballs until you have two groups.
brakamonoga 4/10/2024 10:52 PM
You won’t be able to stop people from cooperating when it works for them. Even if you make it a rule, people will always have plausible deniability, so you can’t enforce a rule telling people they aren’t allowed to have aligned goals. You’d have to find a way to mechanically incentivize playing solo, or backstabbing. That’s the only way to make that work, and implementing a mechanic like that it a balanced way is nearly impossible
10:52 PM
The same thing is true of games like risk. It’s no fun to end up being the faction that everybody is allying against, but there’s no way to enforce a rule against it
Großer Peanut 4/10/2024 10:53 PM
oh yeah I am aware of that. Its unfortunately a mindset issue like I said
10:55 PM
I believe there might be ways to prevent allying from just flat out always being the best option for anyone, but Im too tired to think of anything rn. Just expressing the thoughts that have been marinating in my head about the game lol
brakamonoga 4/10/2024 10:57 PM
The problem with “banning alliances” is that even if you do that, you can’t stop two factions from realizing that their current goals align, and you can’t tell them that they aren’t allowed to have the same goals lol. The only way to effectively bust up alliances would be to give alliances a tangible, significant, and most importantly mechanical risk, beyond simply having your ally backstab you (possibly). Or give solo factions some sort of mechanical benefit, to balance it out
10:57 PM
But anyways, it seems like we’re on the same page lol
Großer Peanut 4/10/2024 10:58 PM
yeah
10:59 PM
honestly its not even possible to give a mechanical penalty because people will just say they arent actually in an alliance, they just happen to not be attacking each other
brakamonoga 4/10/2024 11:00 PM
Exactly. You’d have to “mechanicalize” both the alliance process and the backstabbing process
Großer Peanut 4/10/2024 11:04 PM
ok ive actually had a thought here One thing that could alleviate (not fix) the alliance problem is to change the win condition. Instead of having it be last man standing, you could have a certain number of key states that provide points when controlled, and when any faction controls x amount, they win the game. maybe they have extra draft values too. I feel that this would incentivize more backstabbing and less helpful behavior. All of a sudden helping your ally take a state gets them significantly closer to victory, and maybe gives a draft advantage too that you cant overcome. Im stupid tired rn so i dont think i can explain coherently but uhhh yeah its a thought

Großer Peanut 4/11/2024 1:39 AM
I may be sleepless and rapidly approaching the end of my sanity but I think I cooked here Think about it. Imagine it's Superior and Magnolia ganging up on Appalachia. Each faction needs to control 3 more key states to win. They each take one more from Appalachia, great. Now there's one more of these key states in Appalachia. Who's going to take it? Is superior going to let Magnolia take the last point and only be one point away from victory? That's super risky. There's an inherent incentive to attack each other, as opposed to the current system where there's an incentive to continue to beat up Appalachia and then turn on each other only once they are the last two factions. Also if that rule set is used it would be possible to implement a mechanic where occupied capitals have a chance to rebel every round, with the odds affected by the number of occupying troops. If they rebel, the original owners gain that state and a random number of troops between like 50 and 100 or something. That way no faction is ever permanently out of the game.
